g regime to govern mobility as nations harmonize border and detention policies, outsource state functions to international organizations and private companies, and rely on technologies of governing to discipline the body. The new mobility regime is not only deepening boundaries based on race, class, and gender, it is causing Western nations to embrace a more technocratic, depoliticized understanding of citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Essays.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481806340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774818063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774818063/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles